  <thing id="stChainThatBinds" name="The Chain That Binds" description="You gain one additional Tag skill, which must be one of Energy Weapons, Science, or Repair.\n\nAs a member of the Brotherhood of Steel, you are bound by the chain of command: The Chain that Binds. You must carry out the orders of your immediate superiors, and you are responsible for your subordinate siblings. If you do not carry out your duty, you are expelled from the Brotherhood and your technology will be reclaimed—by any means  necessary." compset="OriginTrait" uniqueness="useronce">
    <tag group="OriginCat" tag="spcBrotherIni"/>
    <eval phase="PreTraits" priority="1000"><![CDATA[perform hero.findchild[Origin].setfocus

doneif (state.isfocus = 0)

focus.field[orMaxTagSkills].value += 1

~additional tag skill must be one of Energy Weapons, Science or Repair
focus.field[orSklChoiceExpr4].text = "component.Skill & !Skill.TagSkill & (thingid.skEnergyWpns|thingid.skScience|thingid.skRepair)"]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="stEducated" name="Educated" description="You have one additional tag skill.  When you fail a skill test using a skill other than a tag skill, the GM gains 1 AP." compset="OriginTrait" summary="Gain an additional Tag Skill of your choice. When you fail a skill test using a skill other than a tag skill, the GM gains 1 AP." uniqueness="useronce">
    <tag group="OriginCat" tag="spcSurvivor"/>
    <tag group="OriginCat" tag="spcTribal"/>
    <eval phase="PreTraits" priority="1000">hero.findchild[Origin].field[orMaxTagSkills].value += 1</eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="stHeavyHanded" name="Heavy Handed" description="Your Melee Damage bonus increases by +1 DC . Your melee and unarmed attacks suffer a complication on a 19 or 20, rather than only a 20." compset="OriginTrait" summary="+1 DC Melee Damage, but unarmed attacks suffer complication on a 19 or 20." uniqueness="useronce">
    <tag group="OriginCat" tag="spcSurvivor"/>
    <tag group="OriginCat" tag="spcTribal"/>
    <eval phase="Setup" priority="1000">#traitbonus[trMeleeDmg] += 1</eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="stNecroticPostHu" name="Necrotic Post-Human" description="You are immune to radiation damage. In fact, you’re healed by it—you regain 1 HP for every 3 points of radiation damage inflicted upon you, and if you rest in an irradiated location, you may re-roll your dice pool when checking if your injuries heal. In addition, Survival becomes a Tag skill, increasing it by 2 ranks.\n\nYou age at a much-decreased rate, and you’re probably older than your unmutated companions—you may even have survived the Great War of 2077—but you’re sterile: “the first generation of ghouls is the last” as the saying goes. You may face discrimination from “smoothskins” (humans who aren’t ghouls), increasing the difficulty or complication range of Charisma tests depending on your opponent’s beliefs." compset="OriginTrait" summary="Immune to Radiation damage. Radiation damage heals 1HP/3 rads, also if resting in irradiated location, may re-roll healing check. Survival becomes a Tag Skill." uniqueness="useronce">
    <tag group="OriginCat" tag="spcGhoul"/>
    <eval phase="Initialize" priority="1000">perform hero.childfound[skSurvival].assign[Skill.TagSkill]
perform hero.assign[Hero.RadImmune]</eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="spcVaultDwellerGh" name="Vault Dweller (Ghoul)" description="When the bombs were falling, you or your predecessors were lucky enough to be safely secured in one of the one hundred and twenty-two Vault-Tec facilities, deep underground protected by thick blast doors and layers of rock and concrete. Your family either had enough money to buy their space or were randomly selected to enter the vault to be saved from the nuclear devastation above—perhaps only to be condemned to immoral experiments run by Vault-Tec on unwitting participants.\n\nYou are free from mutation and disease. The Vault- Tec program has afforded you a safe home for some time, but not without some cost. The vault you came from used you as a human test subject, manipulating your understanding of the world and your behavior in order to study you. That’s left you with a profound psychological change, compared to the survivors on the surface you now know, and affects how you make your way through the wasteland.\n\nWhether through design or poor planning, many of the vaults were not well stocked or prepared for the long wait until nuclear fallout had reached safe levels outside, and many fell into disrepair or out of supplies. Due to these shortcomings, many vault dwellers sought help from the surface, and many vaults opened in order to allow supplies to reach them. By opening their vault doors, the isolated societies inside opened themselves up to mixing with the survivors above, and established a permanent connection with the surface—the most notable example being the residents of Vault 15, who split up and went on to establish the settlement Shady Sands, as well as the raiding gangs of the Jackals, Vipers, and Khans when their vault opened." compset="Origin" uniqueness="unique">
